      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Eutyches</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Eutyches</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/213</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">204</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="155-156"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/482</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Monk, then an archimandrite in Constantinople whose teachings on christology became controversial.<note>not a
                            summary</note>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(<abbr>ca.</abbr> 378 – <abbr>ca.</abbr> 454)</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>His early life, of which hardly anything is known, was evidently as a monk,
                        and then an archimandrite, in Constantinople where, by 448, he and his
                        teaching evidently had an influential following. In Nov. 448 Eusebius <abbr>bp.</abbr> of
                        Dorylaeum denounced his teaching to <abbr>Patr.</abbr> Flavian, and Eutyches was summoned
                        to a synod which condemned him (<ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Zacharias-Pseudo-">Pseudo-Zacharias</ref>,
                        ‘Church History’, II.2; Acts of Council of Chalcedon, First Session). He
                        appealed to Pope Leo I (<hi rend="italic">
                            <abbr>CPG</abbr>
                        </hi> 5948) and to Dioscorus,
                        presenting professions of faith in formulations that were considered
                        acceptable (Leo’s reply also survives [<hi rend="italic">
                            <abbr>CPG</abbr>
                        </hi> 5953]). He
                        was restored at the second Council of Ephesus (449), but under the new
                        emperor Marcian he was condemned again at the Council of Chalcedon in 451,
                        and this time exiled. Exactly what his teaching really was is unclear (both
                        at the time and today), but he was understood to have held that Christ is
                        consubstantial only with the Father, and not with us — a position rejected
                        by both miaphysites and dyophysites.</p>
                </div>
